	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>its not even really about math anymore.  There are slight deviations of blackjack strategy based on how many decks are in the chute, biggest variation being when its a single deck, which is becoming more and more rare in vegas.<br />
<br />
the most common card counting methodology simply has the player keep track of high cards and low cards by starting at 0 and adding 1 for high cards and subtracting 1 for low cards.  the lower the &quot;count&quot; gets, the better chances of your face card coming up, so you increase your bet.<br />
<br />
casinos look for a few signs of counting, and other methods of gambling sometimes fall into these signs.  a popular method among non card counters is bet doubling.  You take your min bet, lets say $5, and your max bet, $20.  everytime you win, you double, and if you lose or get up to your $20 bet, you go back to $5.  If you stay at a table for a long time, with a nice bankroll, you can walk away a pretty healthy winner.  People using this type of method get accused of card counting a lot, because the biggest sign of a card counter is sporadic bet amounts.<br />
<br />
the +/- system barely evens the 51% odds, and the bet doubling rarely nets a huge profit.  the real counters use a more advanced +/- system that would probably straight up own a casino, and the folks using that methodology don't get caught very often.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		<!-- sig -->
			<div>
				__________________<br />
				<br><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=249605><img src=http://www.jade-dragon.net/files/sig.gif align=left></a><br><br> Dephton Disgustipated<br> 70 Erudite Grand Arcanist of Solusek Ro<br> Jade Dragon, Xegony
			</div>
		<!-- / sig -->
		
		
		
	
	</td>
